Sentence: She stayed home because she felt sick.
She : pronoun, third person singular, subject of the verb "stayed"
stayed : verb "stay", past tense, main clause predicate
home : adverb, indicates location, modifies "stayed"
because : subordinating conjunction, introduces reason clause
she : pronoun, third person singular, subject of the verb "felt"
felt : verb "feel", past tense, subordinate clause predicate
sick : adjective, subject complement describing "she"

Sentence: Although it was raining, they went for a walk.
Although : subordinating conjunction, introduces concession clause
it : pronoun, dummy subject referring to weather
was : auxiliary verb "be", past tense, part of progressive aspect
raining : present participle, main verb of subordinate clause
, : punctuation mark separating clauses
they : pronoun, third person plural, subject of the verb "went"
went : verb "go", past tense, main clause predicate
for : preposition, introduces purpose or destination phrase
a : indefinite article, modifies "walk"
walk : noun, object of the preposition "for"

Sentence: Call me when you arrive at the station.
Call : verb, imperative mood, main clause predicate
me : pronoun, first person singular, indirect object of "Call"
when : subordinating conjunction, introduces time clause
you : pronoun, second person, subject of the verb "arrive"
arrive : verb, present tense, subordinate clause predicate
at : preposition, indicates location
the : definite article, modifies "station"
station : noun, object of the preposition "at"

Sentence: If you study hard, you will pass the exam.
If : subordinating conjunction, introduces condition clause
you : pronoun, second person, subject of the verb "study"
study : verb, present tense, subordinate clause predicate
hard : adverb, modifies "study"
, : punctuation mark separating clauses
you : pronoun, second person, subject of the verb "will pass"
will : auxiliary verb, indicates future tense
pass : main verb, infinitive form, part of future predicate
the : definite article, modifies "exam"
exam : noun, direct object of "pass"

Sentence: We cannot enter unless we have a ticket.
We : pronoun, first person plural, subject of the verb "cannot enter"
cannot : modal verb phrase, indicates inability or prohibition
enter : main verb, infinitive form, main clause predicate
unless : subordinating conjunction, introduces negative condition clause
we : pronoun, first person plural, subject of the verb "have"
have : verb, present tense, subordinate clause predicate
a : indefinite article, modifies "ticket"
ticket : noun, direct object of "have"

Sentence: Since he left early, he missed the announcement.
Since : subordinating conjunction, introduces cause clause
he : pronoun, third person singular, subject of the verb "left"
left : verb "leave", past tense, subordinate clause predicate
early : adverb, modifies "left"
, : punctuation mark separating clauses
he : pronoun, third person singular, subject of the verb "missed"
missed : verb, past tense, main clause predicate
the : definite article, modifies "announcement"
announcement : noun, direct object of "missed"

Sentence: While I was cooking, the phone rang.
While : subordinating conjunction, introduces simultaneous time clause
I : pronoun, first person singular, subject of the verb "was cooking"
was : auxiliary verb "be", past tense, part of progressive aspect
cooking : present participle, main verb of subordinate clause
, : punctuation mark separating clauses
the : definite article, modifies "phone"
phone : noun, subject of the verb "rang"
rang : verb "ring", past tense, main clause predicate

Sentence: As soon as the sun set, the bats came out.
As : part of complex subordinating conjunction indicating immediate time
soon : adverb, part of complex conjunction phrase
as : part of complex subordinating conjunction
the : definite article, modifies "sun"
sun : noun, subject of the verb "set"
set : verb, past tense, subordinate clause predicate
, : punctuation mark separating clauses
the : definite article, modifies "bats"
bats : noun, plural, subject of the verb "came"
came : verb "come", past tense, main clause predicate
out : adverb, indicates direction, modifies "came"

Sentence: He smiled because he heard good news.
He : pronoun, third person singular, subject of the verb "smiled"
smiled : verb, past tense, main clause predicate
because : subordinating conjunction, introduces reason clause
he : pronoun, third person singular, subject of the verb "heard"
heard : verb, past tense, subordinate clause predicate
good : adjective, modifies "news"
news : noun, uncountable, direct object of "heard"

Sentence: Although the task was difficult, she finished it on time.
Although : subordinating conjunction, introduces concession clause
the : definite article, modifies "task"
task : noun, subject of the verb "was"
was : verb "be", past tense, linking verb in subordinate clause
difficult : adjective, subject complement describing "task"
, : punctuation mark separating clauses
she : pronoun, third person singular, subject of the verb "finished"
finished : verb, past tense, main clause predicate
it : pronoun, third person singular, direct object of "finished"
on : preposition, indicates time relationship
time : noun, object of the preposition "on"

Sentence: When the bell rings, the class will start.
When : subordinating conjunction, introduces time clause
the : definite article, modifies "bell"
bell : noun, subject of the verb "rings"
rings : verb, present tense, subordinate clause predicate
, : punctuation mark separating clauses
the : definite article, modifies "class"
class : noun, subject of the verb "will start"
will : auxiliary verb, indicates future tense
start : main verb, infinitive form, main clause predicate

Sentence: If it snows tomorrow, school will be closed.
If : subordinating conjunction, introduces condition clause
it : pronoun, dummy subject referring to weather
snows : verb, present tense, subordinate clause predicate
tomorrow : adverb, indicates time, modifies "snows"
, : punctuation mark separating clauses
school : noun, subject of the verb "will be closed"
will : auxiliary verb, indicates future tense
be : auxiliary verb, part of passive voice construction
closed : past participle, adjective functioning as complement in passive voice

Sentence: You won't succeed unless you try your best.
You : pronoun, second person, subject of the verb "won't succeed"
won't : contraction of "will not", auxiliary verb indicating future negation
succeed : main verb, infinitive form, main clause predicate
unless : subordinating conjunction, introduces negative condition clause
you : pronoun, second person, subject of the verb "try"
try : verb, present tense, subordinate clause predicate
your : possessive determiner, modifies "best"
best : noun, direct object of "try"

Sentence: Since we ran out of milk, I went to the store.
Since : subordinating conjunction, introduces cause clause
we : pronoun, first person plural, subject of the verb "ran"
ran : verb "run", past tense, subordinate clause predicate
out : adverb, part of phrasal verb "ran out"
of : preposition, connects verb phrase to object
milk : noun, uncountable, object of the preposition "of"
, : punctuation mark separating clauses
I : pronoun, first person singular, subject of the verb "went"
went : verb "go", past tense, main clause predicate
to : preposition, indicates direction
the : definite article, modifies "store"
store : noun, object of the preposition "to"

Sentence: While he reads the book, his dog sleeps on the rug.
While : subordinating conjunction, introduces simultaneous time clause
he : pronoun, third person singular, subject of the verb "reads"
reads : verb, present tense, subordinate clause predicate
the : definite article, modifies "book"
book : noun, direct object of "reads"
, : punctuation mark separating clauses
his : possessive determiner, modifies "dog"
dog : noun, subject of the verb "sleeps"
sleeps : verb, present tense, main clause predicate
on : preposition, indicates location
the : definite article, modifies "rug"
rug : noun, object of the preposition "on"
